EDUPAGE. This is Edupage, a twice-weekly summary of news items on
information technology. It is provided as a service by EDUCOM -- a
consortium of leading colleges and universities seeking to transform
education through the use of information technology.

WORLDWATCH. While computers could reduce the use of many resources, a
Worldwatch Institute report claims they have actually increased paper
consumption, electricity use, and junk metal (obsolete PCs that are
mothballed rather than recycled).  (Science News, 11/2/93, p. 219)

IBM, KODAK JOIN IN COMPUTER SERVICE CO. IBM and Kodak have joined forces to
establish Technology Service Solutions. The new firm will specialize in
servicing PCs, workstations and electronic devices like supermarket
scanners. (Investor's Business Daily 11/4/93 p.1)

#_#_#_#_#_#_#_#
INTERNET OVERLOAD. Anyone who uses the Internet already knows it-- the
global network is getting overcrowded. The National Center for
Supercomputer Applications reports an increase in World Wide Web requests
from almost 100,000 in June to almost 400,000 in October. Center officials
say "the only solution may be to take a $15 million supercomputer away from
its normal scientific number-crunching duties and employ it full-time as an
electronic librarian." (Tampa Tribune 11/3/93 A9)

COMPUTERIZED HELP ON THE RISE. Automation of consumer-service
representative activities is a hot new area in computing. Help-desk
software is turning up in a variety of businesses, resulting in almost
doubling the number of calls handled per human a day and 60% fewer
call-backs, according to officials at Black & Decker, which installed the
software earlier this year. Dataquest predicts the market will grow to $250
million a year by 1995. (Wall Street Journal, 11/3/93 B1)

