DIGITAL DEBUTS DISK DRIVE. Digital Equipment Corp. announced what it claims
is the most powerful disk drive in its class. The new four-gigabyte model
fits the standard 3.5-inch format used on most PCs. (Investor's Business
Daily 11/4/93 p.4)

HACKER SENTENCED TO YEAR IN PRISON. A 21-year-old computer hacker was
sentenced to a year in prison and 600 hours of community service for
breaking into some of the most sensitive computers used by phone companies
and credit card services. (Miami Herald 11/4/93 A14)

HIGH-FLYING DATA. If your idea of something to do is to fly high in the sky
with your computer, you'll be glad to know that Delta, United and other
airlines will soon be replacing their current in-flight telephones with
ones capable of logging onto computer networks and sending faxes and
e-mail. You will still be able to irritate the people sitting next to you.
(Atlanta Journal/Constitution 11/4/93 C2)

IBM SPEECH RECOGNITION SOFTWARE. IBM will start shipping its Personal
Dictation System software for PCs by year's end. The package has a
32,000-word vocabulary, with much of it oriented toward the medical and
legal professions. The software is considered 97% accurate. (Wall Street
Journal 11/3/93 B6)

#_#_#_#_#_#_#
EC TAKES A LESSON. The European Community is taking notes on U.S. efforts
to build an electronic superhighway. A first step for Europeans will be the
privatization of phone companies in Germany, the Netherlands, Denmark,
Portugal and Greece, anticipated in the next three years. While many
countries are waiting to learn from the American experience, Britain stands
out as a leader and has been praised for "an environment conducive to
(multimedia) initiatives." (Investor's Business Daily 11/3/93 p.13)

ELVIS & NEWTON, PT. II. If you enter Graceland as the "country" in your
personal preferences on Newton, you will find the Newt of the Newton on
your start-up screen instead of the light bulb logo. (Okay, that's all,
folks. No more Newton tricks.)

#_#_#_#_#_#_#_#
THE SOUNDS OF WORK. Telecommuters who want callers to think they're working
in a busy office can buy a 90-minute cassette (from Nextech in St. Louis)
with the sounds of doors closing, phones ringing, typewriters clacking,
drawers banging, and unintelligible voices droning in the background.
Sounds like real work, all right.  But some of us have questions:  Do
people in offices work only 90 minutes a day?  Do they really use
typewriters?  Wouldn't telecommuters rather play a tape filled with surf
sounds? (Atlanta Journal/Constitution 11/3/93 F2)
